            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Present value formula</h2>
              <p>
                Present value (PV) is the value today of money you will receive
                or pay in the future. Because of the time value of money, a
                dollar today is worth more than a dollar tomorrow.
              </p>

              <h3>Single future amount</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1 font-mono text-sm">
                  \( PV = \dfrac{FV}{(1 + r)^n} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-0">where:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-0">
                  <li><strong>PV</strong> = present value today</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>FV</strong> = future value received in the future
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>r</strong> = discount rate per period (e.g., per
                    year)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>n</strong> = number of periods until payment</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>
                Rearranging the formula gives the future value of a present
                amount:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-0">
                  \( FV = PV \times (1 + r)^n \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Multiple cash flows (discounted cash flow)</h3>
              <p>
                For a series of cash flows, discount each one back to today and
                sum them:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-0">
                  \( PV = \sum_{t=0}^{N} \dfrac{CF_t}{(1 + r)^t} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm">
                Here <strong>CF<sub>t</sub></strong> is the cash flow in period
                <strong>t</strong>. Period 0 is today (no discounting), period 1
                is one period from now, and so on.
              </p>

              <h3>Compounding frequency</h3>
              <p>
                If interest is compounded more frequently than once per year,
                convert the nominal annual rate \( r_{\text{annual}} \) to a
                per-period rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-1">
                  \( r_{\text{period}} = \dfrac{r_{\text{annual}}}{m} \)
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-0">
                  \( n_{\text{periods}} = \text{years} \times m \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm">
                where <strong>m</strong> is the number of compounding periods
                per year (12 for monthly, 4 for quarterly, etc.).
              </p>

              <h2>How to use the present value calculator</h2>
              <h3>1. Single cash flow mode</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Select whether you want to solve for <strong>PV</strong> or
                  <strong>FV</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose the compounding frequency (annual, monthly, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter the known value (future or present), the annual discount
                  rate, and the time in years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate</strong> to see the result and the
                  effective number of periods.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. Cash flow stream mode</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the annual discount rate and compounding frequency.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the table to enter cash flows by period. Period 0 is
                  today; later periods are in equal time steps.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add or remove rows as needed. Use negative values for outflows
                  (investments) and positive for inflows.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate PV of stream</strong> to get the total
                  PV and a breakdown by period.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you expect to receive \$5,000 in 4 years, and your
                required return is 7% per year with annual compounding. What is
                the present value?
              </p>
              <p>Using the formula:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-0">
                  \( PV = \dfrac{5{,}000}{(1 + 0.07)^4} \approx
                  \dfrac{5{,}000}{1.3108} \approx 3{,}814. \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                So receiving \$5,000 in 4 years is equivalent to about \$3,814
                today at a 7% discount rate.
              </p>

              <h2>Present value vs. net present value (NPV)</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Present value (PV)</strong> is the value today of one
                  or more future cash flows.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net present value (NPV)</strong> is the sum of the
                  present values of all cash inflows and outflows, including the
                  initial investment.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm">
                In project evaluation, you typically compute NPV. If NPV &gt; 0
                at your required return, the project adds value.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The discount rate is assumed to be constant over the life of
                  the cash flows.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cash flows are assumed to occur at regular intervals (per
                  period).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Risk is captured only through the chosen discount rate;
                  real-world risk may be more complex.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">
                Frequently Asked Questions
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is present value (PV)?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Present value (PV) is the value today of a future cash flow
                    or series of cash flows, discounted at a rate that reflects
                    the time value of money and risk. It answers the question:
                    “How much is this future amount worth in today’s dollars?”
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is the formula for present value of a single future
                      amount?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    The present value of a single future amount FV received in n
                    periods at discount rate r is: PV = FV / (1 +
                    r)<sup>n</sup>, where r is the rate per period (e.g., per
                    year) and n is the number of periods.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >How do I calculate the present value of multiple cash
                      flows?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Discount each cash flow back to today and sum them: PV =
                    Σ[CF<sub>t</sub> / (1 + r)<sup>t</sup>], where CF<sub
                      >t</sub
                    >
                    is the cash flow in period t and r is the discount rate per
                    period. The cash flow stream mode of this calculator does
                    this automatically and shows the discount factor and PV for
                    each period.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What discount rate should I use?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    The discount rate should reflect your opportunity cost and
                    the risk of the cash flows. Common choices include your
                    required rate of return, the company’s cost of capital
                    (WACC), a risk-free rate plus a risk premium, or the
                    interest rate on comparable investments. Higher risk usually
                    means a higher discount rate and a lower present value.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is the difference between present value and net
